sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M10052
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The ehaB part that codes for an autotransporter protein that is on the cell surface. The part can self transport across the bacterial membrane and go to the cell surface. The ehaB part, like other autotransporter proteins, have an N-terminal signal sequence, a passenger domain, and a translocation domain. The ehaB part has also been shown to form biofilms on polystyrene surfaces. The pcr product of the ehaB gene can be digested with XhoI/EcoRI and HindIII and ligated to XhoI/EcoRI-HindIII plasmid pBAD/MycHisA. The expression of the ehaB gene can be placed under control of araBAD promoter. Kanamycin cassette from pUC4K can be inserted into the HindIII site to enable transformation into OS56.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Susan Chen
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Genome of Enterohemorrhagic Escherichia Coli O157:H7 EDL933
